Applies `operator` to two integer inputs: `a` and `b`.A visual shader node for shader parameter (uniform) of type `int`.

A `VisualShaderNodeParameter` of type `int`. Offers additional customization for range of accepted values.Range hint of this node. Use it to customize valid parameter range.The minimum value this parameter can take. `hint` must be either `HINT_RANGE` or `HINT_RANGE_STEP` for this to take effect.The maximum value this parameter can take. `hint` must be either `HINT_RANGE` or `HINT_RANGE_STEP` for this to take effect.The step between parameter's values. Forces the parameter to be a multiple of the given value. `hint` must be `HINT_RANGE_STEP` for this to take effect.The names used for the enum select in the editor. `hint` must be `HINT_ENUM` for this to take effect.If `true`, the node will have a custom default value.Default value of this parameter, which will be used if not set externally. `default_value_enabled` must be enabled; defaults to `0` otherwise.A boolean comparison operator to be used within the visual shader graph.

Returns the boolean result of the comparison between `INF` or `NaN` and a scalar parameter.The comparison function.A visual shader node that returns the depth value of the DEPTH_TEXTURE node in a linear space.

This node can be used in fragment shaders.Linearly interpolates between two values within the visual shader graph.

Translates to `mix(a, b, weight)` in the shader language.Performs a fused multiply-add operation within the visual shader graph.

Uses three operands to compute `(a * b + c)` expression.Calculates an outer product of two vectors within the visual shader graph.

`OuterProduct` treats the first parameter `c` as a column vector (matrix with one column) and the second parameter `r` as a row vector (matrix with one row) and does a linear algebraic matrix multiply `c * r`, yielding a matrix whose number of rows is the number of components in `c` and whose number of columns is the number of components in `r`.Represents the output shader parameters within the visual shader graph.

This visual shader node is present in all shader graphs in form of "Output" block with multiple output value ports.A base type for the parameters within the visual shader graph.

A parameter represents a variable in the shader which is set externally, i.e. from the `ShaderMaterial`. Parameters are exposed as properties in the `ShaderMaterial` and can be assigned from the Inspector or from a script.Name of the parameter, by which it can be accessed through the `ShaderMaterial` properties.Defines the scope of the parameter.A reference to an existing `VisualShaderNodeParameter`.

Creating a reference to a `VisualShaderNodeParameter` allows you to reuse this parameter in different shaders or shader stages easily.The name of the parameter which this reference points to.A visual shader node that accelerates particles.

Particle accelerator can be used in "process" step of particle shader. It will accelerate the particles. Connect it to the Velocity output port.Defines in what manner the particles will be accelerated.A visual shader node that makes particles emitted in a box shape.

`VisualShaderNodeParticleEmitter` that makes the particles emitted in box shape with the specified extents.A visual shader node that makes particles move in a cone shape.

This node can be used in "start" step of particle shader. It defines the initial velocity of the particles, making them move in cone shape starting from the center, with a given spread.A visual shader node that forces to emit a particle from a sub-emitter.

This node internally calls `emit_subparticle` shader method. It will emit a particle from the configured sub-emitter and also allows to customize how its emitted. Requires a sub-emitter assigned to the particles node with this shader.Flags used to override the properties defined in the sub-emitter's process material.A base class for particle emitters.

Particle emitter nodes can be used in "start" step of particle shaders and they define the starting position of the particles. Connect them to the Position output port.If `true`, the result of this emitter is projected to 2D space. By default it is `false` and meant for use in 3D space.A visual shader node that makes particles emitted in a shape defined by a `Mesh`.

`VisualShaderNodeParticleEmitter` that makes the particles emitted in a shape of the assigned `mesh`. It will emit from the mesh's surfaces, either all or only the specified one.The `Mesh` that defines emission shape.If `true`, the particles will emit from all surfaces of the mesh.Index of the surface that emits particles. `use_all_surfaces` must be `false` for this to take effect.A visual shader helper node for multiplying position and rotation of particles.

This node helps to multiply a position input vector by rotation using specific axis. Intended to work with emitters.If `true`, the angle will be interpreted in degrees instead of radians.Visual shader node that defines output values for particle emitting.

This node defines how particles are emitted. It allows to customize e.g. position and velocity. Available ports are different depending on which function this node is inside (start, process, collision) and whether custom data is enabled.Visual shader node for randomizing particle values.

Randomness node will output pseudo-random values of the given type based on the specified minimum and maximum values.A visual shader node that makes particles emitted in a ring shape.

`VisualShaderNodeParticleEmitter` that makes the particles emitted in ring shape with the specified inner and outer radii and height.A visual shader node that makes particles emitted in a sphere shape.

`VisualShaderNodeParticleEmitter` that makes the particles emitted in sphere shape with the specified inner and outer radii.A visual shader node representing proximity fade effect.

The proximity fade effect fades out each pixel based on its distance to another object.A visual shader node that generates a pseudo-random scalar.

Random range node will output a pseudo-random scalar value in the specified range, based on the seed. The value is always the same for the given seed and range, so you should provide a changing input, e.g. by using time.A visual shader node for remap function.

Remap will transform the input range into output range, e.g. you can change a `0..1` value to `-2..2` etc. See `@GlobalScope.remap()` for more details.A node that allows rerouting a connection within the visual shader graph.

Automatically adapts its port type to the type of the incoming connection and ensures valid connections.Returns the port type of the reroute node.Base class for resizable nodes in a visual shader graph.

